A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Airbase Air Defense Systems (ABADS) program element is the principal Air Force (AF) program to provide the ability to detect, track, identify, and defeat airborne
threats to missions and assets. These threats include small-unmanned aircraft systems (sUAS), Rockets, Artillery and Mortars (RAM), and cruise missiles. These
two efforts (Missile Defense (MD) and Counter-small Unmanned Aerial Systems (C-sUAS)) aim to protect personnel, assets, and infrastructure vital to supporting the
national security strategy.

 ABADS MD was originally designed as a configurable combination of Commercial Off the Shelf (COTS)/Government Off the Shelf (GOTS) sensor and Non-Kinetic
 Effector (NKE) technologies integrated with tailored Battle Management Command and Control (BMC2) subsystem that leverages GOTS products and Advanced Battle
 Management System (ABMS) systems to provide adaptive, resilient, and dedicated air defense capability. FY27 adds the integration of kinetic effectors, additional non-
 kinetic effectors and active radar systems. The ABADS MD system is designed to operate independently or in concert with other local and distributed capabilities to form
 a multi-layered defense-in-depth, improving airbase defense and airbase resiliency.

 ABADS MD FY2027 funding continues development efforts to operationalize the NKE following prototype transition from the Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL).
 Additionally, the funding supports integration of short to medium range kinetic effectors, active defense radars, and additional non-kinetic effector capabilities. Funding
 also supports and delivers Government Development Security and Operations (DevSecOps) software pipeline, supporting software updates and prioritized capability
 upgrades. The Government DevSecOps pipeline also supports further alignment with the ABMS portfolio (TOC-L, Digital Infrastructure, and Cloud Based Command and
 Control). FY2027 funding continues support to Director, Operational Test and Evaluation (DOT&E) oversight required test activities.

 ABADS MD FY2027 funding will support testing and integration for the kinetic and non-kinetic effector capabilities. Funding will also support and maintain a Government
 DevSecOps software pipeline, supporting software updates and prioritized capability upgrades. The Government DevSecOps pipeline will also support further alignment
 with the ABMS portfolio (Distributed Battle Management Node, Digital Infrastructure, and Cloud Based Command and Control). FY2027 funding also supports Director,
 Operational Test and Evaluation (DOT&E) oversight required test activities.

 ABADS C-sUAS specifically aims to counter the threats posed by the rapid proliferation of inexpensive yet highly capable systems, and the enemies who target US
 Service members, Allies, and Coalition partners. The ABADS C-sUAS program will continue to analyze evolving threats, evaluate new capabilities, and design an open
 system architecture that reduces life cycle cost and enables fielding to all 180+ DAF installations. ABADS C-sUAS features a system of systems approach to integrate



