       Change Summary Explanation
       The FY 2026 President's Budget submittal did not reflect FY 2027 through FY 2030 funding. Therefore, an explanation of the change between the two budget
       positions for FY 2027 cannot be made in a relevant manner.

       FY 2027 increased compared to FY 2026 by $22.094 million due to a reprioritization of resources within the Department of War (DoW) for 1) enhanced terminal
       performance studies and analysis that will aid the development of nuclear re-entry system technologies and 2) support the additional development of tools for the
       detection and tracking of multi-domain moving target indicators.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Nuclear Technologies                                                                                                                0.000       4.937         5.020
Description: Develop the foundational computational tools and capabilities necessary to advance and sustain national
and international monitoring capabilities and support high-fidelity Modeling & Simulation (M&S) algorithms for enhanced
aerothermodynamic analysis of nuclear re-entry systems.

Nuclear Explosion Monitoring (NEM) activities will improve existing capabilities for monitoring potential clandestine activities and
targets in regions of interest (Air, Ground, & Sea) through the development and use of new sensor technologies, enhanced data
processing algorithms, and expanded M&S capabilities.

Re-entry Aerothermal Science (RAS) activities will develop the tools needed to conduct enhanced nuclear re-entry system
aerothermodynamic analyses underpinning the experimentation and technology modernization of nuclear re-entry system efforts
in PE 0603273F, Science and Technology (S&T) for Nuclear Re-entry Systems.

Research

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Effective FY 2027, activities associated with Re-entry Aerothermal Science (RAS) will transfer to the new Nuclear Re-entry
Systems Science and Technology (S&T) effort aiding enhanced terminal performance research and development supplementing
efforts within PE 0603273F, S&T for Nuclear Re-entry Systems. There will be no reallocation of funding between Nuclear
Technologies and Nuclear Re-entry Systems S&T efforts. Funding previously allocated for RAS within Nuclear Technologies will
be redirected to support NEM activities enabling the expansion of monitoring capabilities for the detection and tracking of multi-
domain moving target indicators.

FY 2026 Plans:
Nuclear Explosion Monitoring:
- Continue utilizing novel computational models and statistical methods to improve uncertainty quantification to better discern and
estimate energetic activities and events.
- Continue developing machine learning algorithms for seismic signal and array processing to enhance near real-time event
detection and discrimination tools.
- Continue developing machine learning for distributed acoustic sensing for noise reduction, detection, data compression, and
source characterization to enhance seismic monitoring, including applications to non-seismic signals.
- Continue developing novel methods for faster, more accurate automated processing of non-seismic data to enhance nuclear
explosion monitoring capabilities.
- Continue advancing and linking 3D source simulations, linear wave propagation simulations, and earth structure models to
enhance prediction capabilities for improved discrimination and characterization of seismic events.
- Commence plans and resourcing strategy for the extension of novel methods and algorithms development for processing non-
seismic data for multi-domain moving target indicator detection and tracking.

Re-entry Aerothermal Science:
- Continue developing foundational nuclear re-entry system Modeling and Simulation (M&S) tools that support advanced Aeroshell
efforts within PE 0603273F, S&T for Nuclear Re-entry Systems.
- Continue aerothermal model validation and improvements to include the development of integrated, comprehensive physics-
based modeling suites to predict aerodynamic flow fields, signatures, and material characterizations.
- Continue enhancing plasma chemistry modeling fidelity through machine learning models and computational chemistry.
- Continue developing computational tools for predicting physics-based effects that result in leading-edge shape change of
hypersonic vehicles.
- Continue weather effects computational tests on nuclear re-entry vehicles and catalogue validation data for M&S tools.
- Continue generating new algorithms for predicting nuclear re-entry vehicle responses to extreme or inclement weather in lower
atmosphere environments.
- Continue analyzing strategic command, control, and communications to identify critical multi-domain technologies.

Research

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Continue developing Modeling and Simulation (M&S) algorithms to inform and support test and integration plans for hypersonic
re-entry flight tests containing government payloads.
- Continue developing M&S algorithms to inform the selection of hypersonic payload technologies (e.g., inertial sensors,
millimeter-wave communications, spectral and hyperspectral sensors, and heatshield materials) for technology maturation
opportunities in future flight tests.
- Continue validating computational results of hypersonic aerothermal chemistry and shock-layer behavior with experimental re-
entry flight test data.
FY 2027 Plans:
Nuclear Explosion Monitoring:
- Continue utilizing novel computational models and statistical methods to improve uncertainty quantification to better discern and
estimate energetic activities and events.
- Continue developing machine learning algorithms for seismic signal and array processing to enhance near real-time events
detection and discrimination tools.
- Continue developing machine learning for distributed acoustic sensing for noise reduction, detection, data compression, and
source characterization to enhance seismic monitoring, including applications to non-seismic signals.
- Continue developing novel methods for faster, more accurate automated processing of non-seismic data to enhance nuclear
explosion monitoring capabilities.
- Continue advancing and linking 3D source simulations, linear wave propagation simulations, and earth structure models to
enhance prediction capabilities for improved discrimination and characterization of seismic events.
