B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025        FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Laser Technology                                                                                                                    46.023         48.840        50.844
Description: High energy laser (HEL) research and development (R&D) includes advancements in continuous wave (CW)
and pulsed laser sources, optical beam combination techniques, optical beam control technologies, optical beam propagation
methodologies, and the integration of these technologies into laboratory-level system demonstration packages . To direct laser
technology development, this effort investigates the lethality of high energy laser weapons against target materials and systems of
interest and develops/employs target engagement analysis tools to determine effective and efficient uses of laser weapon system
technologies to satisfy Department of the Air Force requirements, including counter unmanned aerial systems (c-UAS), counter
intelligence/surveillance/reconnaissance (c-ISR), and counter missiles (c-Missile) for High Value Airborne Asset (HVAA) protection
and point defense.

Activities within this effort directly enable the laser technology demonstration in Program Element 0603605F / Advanced Weapons
Technology, Project 633151 / Directed Energy Technology Development.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue in-house development, validation, and transition of predictive, multi-physics modeling tools required to optimize laser
weapon system concept designs. Activities include: preparing validated models to enable technology demonstration which is
expected to kick off in FY 2027 (PE 0603605F/Project 633151).
- Continue development of laser subsystem technologies to advance the state of the art of continuous wave and pulsed laser
sources, optical beam combination techniques, optical beam control technologies, and laser beam propagation/compensation
techniques. Activities include: preparing technologies for transition into planned laser technology demonstrator system
development expected to kick off in FY 2027 (PE 0603605F/Project 633151).

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Continue in-house development of laser vulnerability models and laser effects assessments for high-priority emerging threat
systems. Activities include preparing critical threat-vulnerability data packages and laser effects data packages to inform laser
system technology demonstrator development expected to kick off in FY 2027 (PE 0603605F/Project 633151).
- Continue efforts to transition high-fidelity, multi-physics, laser and beam-propagation modeling and simulation capabilities that
accurately predicts complex system performance, enabling partners to effectively design and validate laser system performance
before hardware build phase(s). Activities include: finalizing current model versions and transitioning them to the Department of
War and industrial partners.
- Continue participation in Department of War-wide tabletop exercises and wargames via development and implementation
of laser weapon system engagement concepts. activities include: wargame participation and generating critical laser weapon
system employment data (from wargame results) required to design, develop, and demonstrate effective laser weapon system
capabilities.
- Commence development and implementation of in-house model-based systems engineering (MBSE) and digital engineering
constructs. Activities include: developing systems engineering models and workflows to inform planned laser weapon system
demonstrator development expected to kick off in FY 2027 (PE 0603605F/Project 633151) and to direct in-house technology
development that will feed these demonstrations.
FY 2027 Plans:
-Continue in-house development, validation, and transition of predictive, high-fidelity multi-physics modeling tools required to
optimize laser weapon system design concepts. Activities include: validating and deploying models, developing the modeling tools
needed to support future laser weapon system capability demonstrations, and transitioning those tools to industry to help optimize
system performance before the hardware build phase(s).
- Continue development of laser subsystem technologies to advance the state of the art of continuous wave and pulsed laser
sources, optical beam combination techniques, optical beam control technologies, and laser beam propagation/compensation
techniques. Activities include: finalizing technologies for each subsystem to be transitioned into the laser weapon system
capability demonstrator (PE 0603605F/Project 633151), as well as developing new and advancing existing subsystem
technologies needed for future laser weapon system demonstrations.
- Continue in-house development of laser vulnerability models and laser effects assessments for high-priority emerging threat
systems. Activities include: finalizing critical threat-vulnerability and laser effects data packages to support the development of
the laser weapon system capability demonstrator (PE 0603605F/Project 633151), as well as developing additional data packages
needed for future airborne laser weapon system demonstrations.
- Continue participation in Department of War-wide tabletop exercises and wargames via development and implementation of
laser weapon system engagement concepts against targets of interest. Activities include development of laser weapon system
engagement models, wargame participation, and generating the critical laser weapon system employment
data required to design, develop, and demonstrate effective laser weapon system capabilities.

