FY2027.$$, $$The Stand-in Attack Weapon (SiAW) program will utilize a multi-phase approach to migrate advanced technologies and weapon designs into an Model Based System
Engineering (MBSE) environment and then rapidly evolve the designs for an initial capability followed by a more comprehensive capability. The first Phases (1 & 2) have

 been approved as an MTA program and will focus on the integration of key technologies, the implementation of Digital Engineering (DE), a competitive selection, and
 targeted initial capability on a surrogate aircraft in less than 5 yrs, followed by transition to an MCA and integration on the F-35.

 The SiAW MTA for Rapid Prototyping is fully funded. SiAW is postured to conduct the transition from MTA to MCA in FY2027, with the ability to fall back on the AARGM-
 ER interim capability as needed. Budget requests will be updated as required in the outyears to reflect the MCA transition. The US Navy's AARGM-ER provides interim
 combat capability on the F-35 until SiAW production starts.

 The SiAW development effort includes design, development, test, integration, and implementation of appropriate modular open systems approach, related components,
 and efforts, including, but not limited to, logical and physical interfaces defined in Weapon Open System Architecture (WOSA). This approach allows modular and
 severable subsystems, to include those that are software-defined, at the appropriate level to be incrementally added, removed, or replaced throughout the life cycle. Key
 tenets of the SiAW program will be the establishment/use of a MBSE environment, implementation of WOSA, and Agile Software Development.

