FY 2026 Plans:
In the FY 2025 and FY 2026, the Air-to-Air Concept Development effort and funding were reported in Program Element 0603601F/
Conventional Weapons Technology/Project 63670B/Weapon Concept Development. FY 2025 funding was $23.553 million and FY
2026 funding is $20.665 million.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Complete developing the technology trade space to enable air-to-air weapons with robust capability in the future threat
environment, including technologies for efficient propulsion, long-range, high lethality, efficient flight, high agility, miniaturization,
as well as cost and risk reduction for both offensive and defensive purposes.
- Continue developing and testing propulsion systems to enable solid rocket motor performance at low-cost for significantly
increased air-to-air weapon range and load-out. Activities include solid rocket motor design, build, and static tests.
- Continue conducting lethality analysis and ground tests to enable design of small form factor warheads that create tradespace
for other weapon components, enabling larger solid rocket motors for increased range. Activities include leveraging data from
baseline warhead performance, directional fragmentation, and combined effects explosives.
- Continue transitioning advanced target models to other Air Force and Department of War offices. Activities include improving
joint used target models.
- Complete developing preliminary design of air-to-air weapon concepts for sixth- generation platforms, maturing and
demonstrating missile component technologies to increase range and agility.
- Continue exploring and documenting missile flight dynamics trade space. Activities include focusing on maturing and
demonstrating missile component technologies to increase range, loadout, lethality, and agility.
- Stop conducting wind-tunnel experiments to characterize airframes and validate aerodynamic codes leading to development
of highly maneuverable and efficient missiles to counter advanced targets and improve persistence and survivability of future
platforms, enabling air-to-air engagements against highly maneuverable and evasive targets to employ fewer weapons per sortie.
- Continue performing experiments with small warheads to obtain data for lethality analysis to validate and improve designs,
focusing on maturing and demonstrating missile component technology to increase lethality. Activities include warhead design,
development, build, and arena test.
- Continue planning and executing integrated sub-system experiments, focusing on maturing and demonstrating missile
component technologies to increase range, loadout, lethality, and agility. Activities include design, build, and test of modular
sensor arrays and associated hardware.




