       Change Summary Explanation
       The FY 2026 President's Budget submittal did not reflect FY 2027 through FY 2030 funding. Therefore, an explanation of the change between the two budget
       positions for FY 2027 cannot be made in a relevant manner.

       In FY 2025, a decrease of $1.389 million in Other Adjustments was due to realignment of funds to PE 0602212F, Defense Laboratories R&D Projects, to
       implement the Department of War (DoW) Funding Laboratory Enhancements Across Four Categories (FLEX-4) authority under 10 U.S.C Section 4123.

       In FY 2025, an increase of $6.360 million in reprogramming was due to realignment of funds from PE 0601103F, University Research Initiatives and PE
       0601102F, Defense Research Sciences, to meet urgent Department of the Air Force needs.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Affordable Mission Availability                                                                                                 16.606      11.983        11.648
Description: Develop and transition pervasive manufacturing technologies for affordable mission availability of Department of the
Air Force components and systems.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue the advancement of high demand specialized manufacturing technologies including additive manufacturing, robotics
and automation to develop cost effective conventional production, overhaul, and specialty material repair technologies to enable
affordable sustainment of legacy aircraft systems.
- Continue the development of cost-effective manufacturing and repair processes such as modular battery manufacturing, turbine
engine repair processes, and automation to reduce touch labor to meet specific needs of Programs of Record and depots to
increase mission availability due to decreased maintenance down time.
- Continue the development and transition of manufacturing technologies to meet the performance and production demands of
hypersonic weapons and components. Content responsive to Program Executive Office (PEO) needs of multiple fielded systems
as well as future systems and includes developing manufacturing processes for high temperature windows, weapons structure,
major subsystems and sensors.
- Continue the development and demonstration of the manufacturability of materials, processes and devices for command and
control communication technologies, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance systems, and radio frequency (RF), digital and
high power electronic devices.
- Continue manufacturing technologies for high temperature sensors and windows.
- In collaboration with industry Primes and their suppliers, develop new manufacturing methods, technologies and processes
to solve cost and manufacturing rate issues that are likely to cause future production failures of Department of the Air Force
programs of record. Examples include developing additional manufacturing sources for bottleneck components that drive low
production yields and long delays, particularly in high volume advanced aircraft and rapid production munitions programs. The
pervasive application of this research to multiple programs of record explains funding in the Manufacturing Technologies program
rather than in individual programs of record.
FY 2027 Plans:

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Complete the advancement of high demand specialized manufacturing technologies including additive manufacturing, robotics
and automation to develop cost effective conventional production, overhaul, and specialty material repair technologies to enable
affordable sustainment of legacy aircraft systems.
- Continue the development of cost-effective manufacturing and repair processes such as modular battery manufacturing, turbine
engine repair processes, and automation to reduce touch labor to meet specific needs of Programs of Record and depots to
increase mission availability due to decreased maintenance down time. Activities include:
-- Validation of the performance of radio frequency (RF) photonics cable technology for electronic warfare systems delivering an
8x reduction in maintenance labor and 75% weight savings as compared to traditional RF coax cables.
- Complete the development and transition of manufacturing technologies to meet the performance and production demands of
hypersonic weapons and components. Content responsive to Program Executive Officer (PEO) needs of multiple fielded systems
as well as future systems and includes developing manufacturing processes for high temperature windows, weapons structure,
major subsystems and sensors.
- Continue the development and demonstration of the manufacturability of materials, processes and devices for command and
control communication technologies, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance systems, and RF, digital and high-power
electronic devices. Activities include:
-- Development of qualification lots and delivery of prototype test results of low-cost advanced transceivers used to create
affordable mass electronic warfare effects that counter current and future threat systems.
- Finalize wafer process and packaging development efforts for pervasive compact RF photonic components enabling a 100x
production capacity increase, 10x cost savings, and 5x performance improvement. Activities include:
-- Maturation of manufacturing processes to manufacturing readiness level (MRL) 6 for a specialized electronic transistor resulting
in a 4x yield improvement and a 50% cost reduction. This technology will extend the operational frequency range providing ultra-
high data rates and higher resolution for imaging, precision radars, and remote sensing applications.
-- Reduction in the manufacturing efforts that validate advanced electronic warfare capabilities for future weapon systems.
- In collaboration with industry Primes and their suppliers, continue development new manufacturing methods, technologies and
processes to solve cost and manufacturing rate issues that are likely to cause future production failures of Department of the Air
Force programs of record. Examples include developing additional manufacturing sources for bottleneck components that drive
low production yields and long delays, particularly in high volume advanced aircraft and rapid production munitions programs. The
pervasive application of this research to multiple programs of record explains funding in the Manufacturing Technologies program
rather than in individual programs of record. Activities include:
-- Expansion of the Defense Industrial Base for transparency systems by establishing critical manufacturing processes at a new
supplier. Complete development of an advanced coating system tailored to meet specific weapon system requirements and a
demonstration of the coating operation at 50% scale.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Funding in FY 2027 decreased compared to FY 2026 by $0.335 million due to completion of research for high demand specialized
manufacturing technologies for affordable sustainment of legacy systems and transitioning manufacturing technologies for
hypersonic weapons and components. This reduction reflects programmatic adjustments to the DAF Science and Technology
portfolio for strategic realignment to optimize core research areas and improve resource efficiency.
Title: Advanced Manufacturing Technologies                                                                                          13.833      17.084         16.546
Description: Develop and transition affordable advanced manufacturing for Department of the Air Force fielded and future
weapon systems.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue to enable advanced manufacturing processes, techniques, and equipment availability through automation, robotics,
mixed reality and digital transformations for reducing materiel weapons acquisition, maintenance and repair costs.
- Continue the development and demonstration of digital engineering concepts into manufacturing processes for reduced design-
through production cycle times, and reduced weapons systems costs. Examples include 1) the development of tools to utilize
block chain technology for seamless and secure share manufacturing throughout the Prime manufacturer's supply chain and with
the Department of the Air Force (DAF) Program Office and 2) the development of digital design and modeling tools that enable
rapid, high quality assembly of parts from multiple manufacturers.
- Accelerate the development, demonstration, and evaluation of additively manufactured aerospace components and
subcomponents to address diminishing manufacturing sources issues of original designed parts no longer available/produced and
to produce previously unmanufacturable part geometries/shapes for increased performance.
- Complete the development and demonstration of technologies that enable the factory of the future, digital supply chain
management, and industrial internet of things.
- Commence the development of tools to rapidly develop digital models of parts under depot repair to enable rapid automation of
repair processes currently completed through touch labor.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Continue to enable advanced manufacturing processes, techniques, and equipment availability through automation, robotics,
mixed reality and digital transformations for reducing materiel weapons acquisition, maintenance and repair costs.
- Continue the development and demonstration of digital engineering concepts into manufacturing processes for reduced design
through production cycle times, and reduced weapons systems costs. Examples include 1) the development of tools to utilize
block chain technology for seamless and secure share manufacturing throughout the Prime manufacturer's supply chain and with
the Department of the Air Force (DAF) Program Office and 2) the development of digital design and modeling tools that enable
rapid, high quality assembly of parts from multiple manufacturers. Activities include:
-- Testing and validation of pre-assembled kits for large-scale composite assembly approaches.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Accelerate the development, demonstration, and evaluation of additively manufactured aerospace components and
subcomponents to address diminishing manufacturing sources issues of original designed parts no longer available/produced and
to produce previously unmanufacturable part geometries/shapes for increased performance. Activities include:
-- Demonstration of autonomous robotic forming for production of long-lead forged components.
- Continue the development of tools to rapidly develop digital models of parts under depot repair to enable rapid automation of
repair processes currently completed through touch labor. Activities include:
