C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
- Complete the advancement of high demand specialized manufacturing technologies including additive manufacturing, robotics
and automation to develop cost effective conventional production, overhaul, and specialty material repair technologies to enable
affordable sustainment of legacy aircraft systems.
- Continue the development of cost-effective manufacturing and repair processes such as modular battery manufacturing, turbine
engine repair processes, and automation to reduce touch labor to meet specific needs of Programs of Record and depots to
increase mission availability due to decreased maintenance down time. Activities include:
-- Validation of the performance of radio frequency (RF) photonics cable technology for electronic warfare systems delivering an
8x reduction in maintenance labor and 75% weight savings as compared to traditional RF coax cables.
- Complete the development and transition of manufacturing technologies to meet the performance and production demands of
hypersonic weapons and components. Content responsive to Program Executive Officer (PEO) needs of multiple fielded systems
as well as future systems and includes developing manufacturing processes for high temperature windows, weapons structure,
major subsystems and sensors.
- Continue the development and demonstration of the manufacturability of materials, processes and devices for command and
control communication technologies, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance systems, and RF, digital and high-power
electronic devices. Activities include:
-- Development of qualification lots and delivery of prototype test results of low-cost advanced transceivers used to create
affordable mass electronic warfare effects that counter current and future threat systems.
- Finalize wafer process and packaging development efforts for pervasive compact RF photonic components enabling a 100x
production capacity increase, 10x cost savings, and 5x performance improvement. Activities include:
-- Maturation of manufacturing processes to manufacturing readiness level (MRL) 6 for a specialized electronic transistor resulting
in a 4x yield improvement and a 50% cost reduction. This technology will extend the operational frequency range providing ultra-
high data rates and higher resolution for imaging, precision radars, and remote sensing applications.
-- Reduction in the manufacturing efforts that validate advanced electronic warfare capabilities for future weapon systems.
- In collaboration with industry Primes and their suppliers, continue development new manufacturing methods, technologies and
processes to solve cost and manufacturing rate issues that are likely to cause future production failures of Department of the Air
Force programs of record. Examples include developing additional manufacturing sources for bottleneck components that drive
low production yields and long delays, particularly in high volume advanced aircraft and rapid production munitions programs. The
pervasive application of this research to multiple programs of record explains funding in the Manufacturing Technologies program
rather than in individual programs of record. Activities include:
-- Expansion of the Defense Industrial Base for transparency systems by establishing critical manufacturing processes at a new
supplier. Complete development of an advanced coating system tailored to meet specific weapon system requirements and a
demonstration of the coating operation at 50% scale.
